## 🌐 Spring Boot Rules

### Structure
- Controllers → controller/
- Services (interface + impl) → service/
- Repositories → repository/
- Entities → entity/
- DTOs → dto/
- Kafka events + listeners → event/
- Config classes → config/
- Utilities → util/

### Mandatory Patterns
- ALWAYS use DTOs — never return JPA entities from controllers
- ALWAYS @Transactional on service methods that write to DB
- ALWAYS ResponseEntity<ApiResponse<T>> on all endpoints
- ALWAYS @Valid on all @RequestBody parameters
- ALWAYS use GlobalExceptionHandler with @RestControllerAdvice
- ALWAYS @PreAuthorize for role-based access
- NEVER put business logic in controllers
- NEVER expose password or sensitive fields in DTOs
- NEVER hardcode secrets — always use ${ENV_VAR} from application.properties

### ApiResponse wrapper (always use this):
```java
public class ApiResponse<T> {
    private boolean success;
    private T data;
    private String message;
    private LocalDateTime timestamp;
}
```

### Auth
- JwtAuthFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter
- JwtUtil: generateToken, validateToken, extractUsername
- SecurityConfig with SecurityFilterChain bean
- BCryptPasswordEncoder for passwords
- Client sends: Authorization: Bearer <token>

### Kafka
- Topics as constants in a KafkaTopics class
- Producers: KafkaTemplate<String, Object>
- Consumers: @KafkaListener in event/ package
- Serialize/deserialize as JSON with Jackson

### Cloudinary
- All operations via util/CloudinaryService.java
- Credentials from environment variables only
- Store only the URL string in the database
- Never store binary files in PostgreSQL

